references: There are two general approaches to address/tackle this problem. One line of research dedicated to so-called local methods suggests to do more computational work before each communication in the hope that those would increase the worth/impact/value of the information to be communicated (Goyal u.â€‰a., 2017; Wangni u.â€‰a., 2018; Stich, 2018; Khaled u.â€‰a., 2020). An alternative approach investigates inexact/lossy information compression strategies which aim to send approximate but relevant information encoded with less number of bits. In this work we focus on the second approach of compressed learning. Research in this latter stream splits into two orthogonal directions. To explore savings in communication, various (mostly randomized) compression operators have been proposed and analyzed such as random sparsification (KoneÄnÃ½ und RichtÃ¡rik, 2018; Wangni u.â€‰a., 2018), Top-kğ‘˜k sparsification (Alistarh u.â€‰a., 2018), standard random dithering (Goodall, 1951; Roberts, 1962; Alistarh u.â€‰a., 2017), natural dithering (HorvÃ¡th u.â€‰a., 2019a), ternary quantization (Wen u.â€‰a., 2017), and sign quantization (Karimireddy u.â€‰a., 2019b; Bernstein u.â€‰a., 2018, 2019; Liu u.â€‰a., 2019; Safaryan und RichtÃ¡rik, 2019). TableÂ 1 summarizes the most common compression methods with their variances and the number of encoding bits.

In all cases, the iteration complexity depends on the variance of the underlying compression scheme and grows as more compression is applied. For this reason, we are interested in compression methods which save in communication by using less bits and minimize iteration complexity by introducing lower variance. However, intuitively and also evidently from TableÂ 1, these two goals are in fundamental conflict, i.e. requiring fewer bits to be communicated in each round introduces higher variance, and demanding small variance forces more bits to be communicated.

Furthermore, notice that compression operators can achieve zero variance in some settings, e.g. ternary or scaled sign quantization when d=1ğ‘‘1d=1 (see Table 1). On the other hand, the UP (3) implies that the normalized variance Î±>0ğ›¼0\alpha>0 for any finite bits bğ‘b. The reason for this inconsistency comes from the fact that, for instance, the binary32 format encodes any number with 32 bits and the error 2âˆ’32superscript2322^{-32} is usually ignored in practice.
